  <main>
    <!-- Introduction (with hidden heading for screen readers) -->
    <section>
      <h2 class="visually-hidden">Introduction</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Sati Shankar</strong> — full name Sati Shankar Dutta Pandey, Ph.D.,  — is an Indian independent scholar, author, applied mathematician, and Vedic researcher based in New Delhi, Bharat (India). He is the Founder and Chief Functionary of the Global Synergetic Foundation (GSFN, est. 1992), a multidisciplinary research and knowledge organisation, and the principal author of the Astitva Series (ISSN: 2454-602X), an open-access scholarly series published by GSFN exploring the deep structures of consciousness, civilisation, and knowledge.

      </p>
      <p>
        His academic formation spans the natural sciences and humanities. He received his Bachelor degree in 1981 (First Class First in Institution) from the University of Gorakhpur, with studies in Physics, Chemistry, Biology, Psychology — including Experimental Psychophysics, Physiological Psychology, and Abnormal Psychology — and Philosophy, covering both Symbolic Logic and Indian and Western traditions. He then pursued postgraduate studies in Mathematical Economics and Econometrics at Banaras Hindu University (BHU), Varanasi, earning his Master's degree in 1983 as First in Order of Merit and recipient of both the Wagle Gold Medal and the BHU Gold Medal. His doctoral research (Ph.D., BHU, 1991) addressed the intersecting domains of Mathematical Control Systems, the Economics of Information, and Psycho-physiological Behavioural Science, with a focus on decision-making and the structure of organisations.

      </p>

  <p>
        His subsequent work has ranged across Complex Systems and Synergetics, International Strategic Management, Logic and Philosophy of Science, Sanskrit Studies, Rig Veda, Ayurveda (Ayurveda Ratna), and Bharatiya Darshana (Indian philosophical traditions). His earliest published research — a paper on the Theory of Expectation presented at the Indian Science Congress — led to inclusion in Reference Asia: Asia's Who's Who of Men and Women of Achievement.
   </p>

  <p>
       He has been a Fellow of the Royal Asiatic Society, Great Britain and Ireland (elected 2007), and holds life membership in the Indian Mathematical Society, Indian Econometric Society, Indian Association of General Relativity and Gravitation (IAGRG), Indian Science Congress Association (ISCA), Indian Philosophical Congress, Akhil Bharatiya Darshan Parishad, and the Wider Association for Vedic Studies (WAVES), an affiliate of the World Association for Vedic Studies (USA) and the International Association of Sanskrit Studies (IASS). He has also been a member of the Econometric Society (US), the Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics (SIAM), the Institute of Physics (IOP), and IEEE (US).

   </p>

  <p>
       His writing in the Astitva Series draws on this entire formation — scientific rigour, philosophical depth, and the living tradition of Bharatiya Darshana — to produce open inquiry for scholars, thinkers, and thoughtful general readers.


    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Research Orientation</h2>
      <p>
        The research program associated with Sati Shankar focuses on examining conceptual structures embedded in classical intellectual traditions and exploring their implications for contemporary theoretical discussions in philosophy of science, mathematical reasoning, and cognitive frameworks.
      </p>
      <p>
        This work often involves close textual analysis of historical sources together with systematic philosophical reflection on their structural and methodological implications.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Institutional Role</h2>
      <p>
        Sati Shankar founded the <strong>Global Synergetic Foundation (GSFN)</strong> as an independent platform for interdisciplinary research and scholarly publishing. Through this initiative he oversees the development of research projects and the publication infrastructure associated with the <strong>Astitva series</strong>.
      </p>
    </section>

